DESCRIPTION: In accordance with (usually for tabulated or illustrated data)
a value or something in between two other values or objects
a value is less than another value
a value is greater or equal than another value
Spatial relation class: topology (i.e. contact). Often also involves aspects of proximity and orientation, just only strictly contact.
Can refer to type hierarchy (ontology) "A is a B". Can also describe a condition that an object might satisfy, e.g. "A is (next to) B", "A is red" ...
If interpreted spatially then synonym with "adjacent"
Strictly a temporal quantifier, but often used to denote an axiom that every instance of an object satisfied, e.g. "It must always be the case that ..."
If interpreted spatially, spatial relation class is either mereology (part of) or topology (containment). Otherwise can refer to a property/feature that the object satisfies.
connect an object with another object, e.g. an accessible route connects accessible units to service areas. Spatial relation class: topology.
something is a part of another thing, e.g. an ancillary space is part of the main firecell, i.e. they have the same riskGroup. Spatial relation class: mereology.
mathematical operator - also called set membership
